    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.35b.31"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">31</fw>
                
                <fw type="letterhead">
                    <hi rend="caps">THE COLLEGE OF WOOSTER
                        <lb/>
                    WOOSTER, OHIO 44691
                        <lb/>
                        
                    DEPARTMENT OF MATHEMETICS</hi>
                </fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>September 17, 1971</dateline>
                
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>Mr. John <hi rend="caps">G.</hi> Neihardt</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Skyrim Farm</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Route 7</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Columbia, Missouri</addrLine>
                    </address>
                
                    <salute>Dear Mr. Neihardt:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I am writing to ask you the favor of giving me permission to quote two stanzas from your poem <hi rend="underline">The Poet's Town</hi> in, of all places!, a chapter in a mathematics book on Elementary Functions being published by the Macmillan Company. I have long liked the poem, andthe<sic>and the</sic> two stanzas
                <lg>
                    <l>Once in a cycle the comet</l>
                    <l>Doubles its lonesome track</l>
                    <l>Enriched with the tears of a thousand years</l>
                    <l>Aeschylus wanders back.</l>
                </lg>
                <lg>
                    <l>Ever inweaving, returning,</l>
                    <l>The near grows out of the far;</l>
                    <l>And Homer shall sing once more in a swing</l>
                    <l>Of the austere polar star,</l>
                </lg>
                struck me as an admirable introduction to the chapters on the trigonometric functions as a representative of the ebb and flow of cyclic, pulsing changes.</p>
                
                <p>If I may have your permission to use these, I shall be most grateful for the chance to use them, and I enclose a stamped, return envelope in the hope that you may be willing to grant it.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Sincerely yours,</salute>
                
                    <signed>Melcher P. Fobes.</signed>
                    <signed>Melcher P. Fobes
                    Professor of Mathematics
                    The College of Wooster</signed>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
        </body>
        
